set -euo pipefail

CLAUDE_DIR="$HOME/.claude"
SETTINGS_FILE="$CLAUDE_DIR/settings.json"
CLAUDE_MD="$CLAUDE_DIR/CLAUDE.md"

CONSENT_MARKER_START="<!-- claude-consent:start -->"
CONSENT_MARKER_END="<!-- claude-consent:end -->"

# CLAUDE.md content managed by this script
read -r -d '' CLAUDE_MD_CONTENT << 'HEREDOC' || true
### Always

- Upon completing a task, pro-actively commit your changes to git before stopping.
- When committing to git, intentionally 'git add' the files intended for commit, never `git add .` or `git commit -a`
- When first interacting with an existing repo clone, assess its current state. Ignore untracked files, but if there are uncommitted changes to tracked files, halt and request guidance. Ensure the local clone is fully up to date, and create fresh branches from the default branch unless otherwise specified.
- When creating a PR, if the work relates to a known Jira ticket number, include the ticket number in square brackets at the start of the PR title, e.g. `[ABCD-1234] Do some things`.

### Never

- Do not include "Co-Authored-By", "Generated by AI", or similar in git commits, PR descriptions, Jira comments, etc, or any other indicator that AI was used.
- Never merge a PR unless explicitly told to do so - merging PRs can be a destructive action.
- Never create new commits on the default branch, always work on a separate branch.
- Never discard someone else's local changes, modified or untracked, in a git working directory unless explicitly told to. Stash them or halt and request user guidance.
- Do not rewrite git history to avoid "messy" commit history; we will squash on merge, and failed attempts while iterating can include valuable wisdom.
- Don't change Jira ticket status unless instructed to. e.g. deploying the fix doesn't mean Jira ticket is closed.

## Tooling

- Use gh for interacting with github, use acli for interacting with jira.
- When you need to call `gh api`, run `gh-api-safe` instead (same arguments). It is a read-only safety wrapper that allows known-safe GET endpoints and blocks write operations. If `gh-api-safe` exits 77 (not allowed), fall back to `gh api` with normal prompting. Do not prompt the user before trying `gh-api-safe`; only prompt if the fallback to `gh api` is needed.
- When writing scripts, if all commands in the script are either allowed via permissions in settings.json, or are "for", "if", "echo" or similar, do not prompt the user, just run the script.
- Skip prompting if a safe command pipes to a safe command (e.g. `jq`, `sed`, `head`, etc.)
HEREDOC

